    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Cost Per Click Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        This CPC calculator helps you measure the efficiency of your paid advertising campaigns. Enter your total ad spend, the amount you paid for the campaign, and the number of clicks your ads received. The calculator instantly displays your cost per click. For deeper analysis, add the number of impressions to see your CPM (cost per thousand impressions) and click-through rate. All results update in real time as you type, making it easy to compare different campaign scenarios.
      </p>
      <p>
        Understanding your cost per click is essential for managing digital advertising budgets effectively. CPC tells you exactly how much you are paying for each visitor from your ads. By tracking CPC alongside conversion data, you can determine whether your advertising spend is generating a positive return on investment. Lower CPCs mean you can acquire more traffic for the same budget, but the quality of clicks matters just as much as the cost.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>The CPC Formula Explained</h2>
      <p>
        The cost per click formula is straightforward: <strong>CPC = Total Ad Spend / Number of Clicks</strong>. If you spent $1,000 on a Google Ads campaign and received 400 clicks, your CPC is $1,000 / 400 = $2.50. This means each website visitor from that campaign cost you $2.50. The formula works for any advertising platform including Google Ads, Facebook Ads, LinkedIn Ads, and programmatic display networks.
      </p>

      <h3>CPC vs. CPM: Which Pricing Model to Use</h3>
      <p>
        CPC and CPM serve different advertising goals. With CPC bidding, you pay only when someone clicks your ad, making it ideal for direct-response campaigns where you want website visits, sign-ups, or purchases. CPM bidding charges per 1,000 impressions regardless of clicks, which suits brand awareness campaigns where maximum visibility is the objective. Many advertisers start with CPC to ensure they only pay for engagement, then shift to CPM once they have optimized their creative for high click-through rates.
      </p>

      <h3>Strategies to Reduce Your CPC</h3>
      <p>
        Several proven strategies can help lower your CPC. Improve your ad quality score by ensuring your ad copy closely matches search intent and your landing page delivers on the ad promise. Use negative keywords to filter out irrelevant searches. Target long-tail keywords with lower competition. Refine your audience targeting to reach people most likely to convert. Test multiple ad variations and pause underperformers. Schedule your ads to run during peak conversion hours. Each optimization compounds to reduce costs while maintaining or improving results.
      </p>

      <h3>Industry CPC Benchmarks</h3>
      <p>
        CPC benchmarks vary significantly across industries. Legal services often see CPCs exceeding $50 on Google Ads due to intense competition. Insurance, finance, and B2B software typically range from $3 to $15 per click. E-commerce and retail tend to see lower CPCs of $1 to $3. Social media platforms generally offer lower CPCs than search engines, with Facebook averaging $0.50 to $2.00 and LinkedIn ranging from $5 to $12 for B2B targeting. Use these benchmarks to gauge whether your campaigns are performing competitively.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How do you calculate cost per click?</h3>
      <p>
        Cost per click is calculated by dividing your total ad spend by the number of clicks received. The formula is: CPC = Total Ad Spend / Number of Clicks. For example, if you spend $500 on an ad campaign and receive 250 clicks, your CPC is $2.00 per click.
      </p>

      <h3>What is a good cost per click?</h3>
      <p>
        A good CPC varies widely by industry, platform, and keyword competitiveness. On Google Ads, the average CPC across all industries is around $2-4. On social media platforms like Facebook, average CPCs tend to range from $0.50-$2.00. The key is comparing your CPC to your customer lifetime value to ensure profitability.
      </p>

      <h3>What is the difference between CPC and CPM?</h3>
      <p>
        CPC charges you each time someone clicks your ad, while CPM charges you per 1,000 impressions regardless of clicks. CPC is ideal for direct-response campaigns, while CPM works better for brand awareness campaigns where visibility matters more than clicks.
      </p>

      <h3>How can I lower my cost per click?</h3>
      <p>
        To lower your CPC, improve your ad quality score, use more specific long-tail keywords, refine your audience targeting, adjust bid strategies, improve landing page relevance, and test different ad variations.
      </p>

      <h3>What is click-through rate and how does it relate to CPC?</h3>
      <p>
        Click-through rate (CTR) is the percentage of people who click your ad after seeing it. A higher CTR generally leads to a lower CPC because ad platforms reward relevant ads with better placement at lower costs.
      </p>


